# Technical Audit of DIDKit WASM Integration for Vela Network Phase 1

## 1. Internal DID Resolution During Verification

DIDKit performs **automatic DID resolution** as part of verifying a credential or JWS. When you call `didkit_vc_verify_credential` or `didkit_vc_verify_presentation`, the library will internally resolve the **issuer’s DID** (or the DID in the proof’s verification method or JWS header) to obtain the DID Document. DIDKit bundles support for many DID methods (e.g. did:key, did:web, did:ethr, did:pkh, did:ion, etc.) via the `ssi` library ([GitHub - spruceid/didkit: A cross-platform toolkit for decentralized identity.](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit#:~:text=DIDKit%20provides%20Verifiable%20Credential%20and,which%20contains%20the%20core%20functionality)) ([didkit - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit#:~:text=,tz%20%5E0.2.0%20normal)). It determines the DID method from the prefix (e.g. `"did:key"`) and uses the corresponding resolver implementation to fetch or generate the DID Document. For example, in the C test code, one can explicitly call `didkit_did_resolve(did, options)` to fetch a DID Document; this returns a JSON string containing the resolution result (with a `"didDocument"` field) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Resolve%20DID)). In verification, this resolution step happens under the hood (so you typically **do not need to call** `didkit_did_resolve` manually before verification – DIDKit will handle it).

Once the DID Document is obtained, **DIDKit selects the appropriate verification method** from it to check the signature. In a Linked Data Proof, the credential’s `proof.verificationMethod` property usually specifies a DID URL referencing the public key used to sign. DIDKit will **dereference that DID URL** against the DID Document to retrieve the public key material ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20,NULL)). In the case of a JWT credential, the JOSE header’s `kid` is expected to contain a DID or DID URL identifying the key; DIDKit will similarly resolve that. If no `kid` is present, DIDKit may fall back to using the issuer DID and select a key (e.g. the first appropriate key, though omitting `kid` is not recommended for multi-key DIDs).

**Proof purpose and controller validation:** DIDKit ensures that the signer actually controls the DID by verifying that the key used is authorized for the intended purpose in the DID Document. The W3C Verifiable Credentials data model defines a `proofPurpose` (e.g. `assertionMethod` for credentials or `authentication` for presentations) which indicates the relationship the key must have in the DID Document. During verification, DIDKit checks that the resolved DID Document contains the verification method in the corresponding field. For example, if a credential’s proof has `proofPurpose: "assertionMethod"`, the DID Document must list that key in its **`assertionMethod` array**. This ensures the DID controller intended that key for asserting credentials. Likewise, for an authentication proof (such as a DIDAuth presentation), the key must be in the DID’s **`authentication` array**. These checks are handled internally by DIDKit’s verification routines. (In the DIDKit API, you also provide the expected proof purpose as an option when verifying – see below – which helps DIDKit enforce the proper relationship.) If the key is not found in the correct verification relationship, or if the DID resolution fails or the signature is invalid, DIDKit will mark the verification as failed. The verification result is returned as a JSON report containing any errors. For instance, after a successful verification, the result JSON has an empty errors array (`"errors": []`), whereas an invalid proof or DID binding would populate an error message ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Avc_verify_options%20%3D%20,assertionMethod)).

**Verification options in Python (Wasmtime) for proper resolution:** When invoking the WASM verification functions from Python, you should pass the appropriate JSON options string to ensure DIDKit knows how to handle the proof. Specifically:
- **`proofPurpose`**: It’s recommended to specify this in the options for verification. For example, to verify a Verifiable Credential you might pass `{"proofPurpose": "assertionMethod"}` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vc_options%2C%20sizeof%20vc_options%2C%20)), and for a Verifiable Presentation used in authentication, `{"proofPurpose": "authentication"}` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)). This option tells DIDKit which verificationMethod relationship to require in the DID Document (though DIDKit can also infer it from the proof itself, explicitly providing it aligns with what you expect and adds a safety check).
- **`proofFormat`**: This is crucial when dealing with JWT-based credentials or presentations. By default, `didkit_vc_verify_credential` assumes the input is a JSON-LD credential with an embedded proof. If you instead are verifying a JWS (compact JWT), you must pass `{"proofFormat": "jwt"}` in the options so that DIDKit knows to treat the input string as a JWT ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=vc_verify_options%20%3D%20)). The same applies to presentations (`didkit_vc_verify_presentation`) that are JWT-based (DIDKit will parse the JWT, extract `iss`, `kid`, etc., and resolve the DID as needed).
- **`challenge` and `domain`**: If you are verifying a challenge/response (e.g. a DID Authentication flow), you should supply the expected challenge and domain in the verification options. DIDKit will then check that the presentation’s proof contains the matching challenge and domain. In the test example, when verifying a DIDAuth presentation, they included the `challenge` in the options: `{"proofPurpose": "authentication", "challenge": "<expected value>"}` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)). This ensures the proof’s challenge equals what the verifier sent, preventing replay attacks.
- **No explicit resolver needed:** You do *not* need to manually provide a DID document to DIDKit or call a separate resolution function during verify – simply ensure the DID method is one that DIDKit supports and that any required network configuration is in place (for methods like did:web or did:ion, DIDKit may perform an HTTP lookup; in a pure WASM environment with no network, those might need stub resolution or pre-loaded DID documents). If needed, DIDKit allows passing DID resolution input options as a second parameter to `didkit_did_resolve` or `didkit_did_url_dereference` (in JSON), but for most use cases, passing `NULL` or `{}` uses defaults ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Resolve%20DID)). In summary, the Python code’s main responsibility is to pass the correct verification options JSON string and the credential/presentation to verify. DIDKit will handle DID resolution and key lookup internally, using the proof data and the options provided.

## 2. Concrete WASM Interface Specification

The `didkit.wasm` module exports a **C-style interface** that you can call from any host language capable of interacting with WebAssembly (in this case, Python via Wasmtime). All functions expect and return data as pointers in linear memory, typically as C strings (null-terminated UTF-8). **Memory management** follows a simple model: when DIDKit returns a string, it allocates it in the WASM module’s memory and expects the caller to free it by calling `didkit_free_string`. On error, functions generally return `NULL` (a null pointer) and an error message can be retrieved via `didkit_error_message`. Below is a full list of the key exports in `didkit.wasm`, with their usage details:

### Key Management Functions
- **`didkit_vc_generate_ed25519_key()` → `*const c_char`** – Generates a new Ed25519 key pair and returns a JWK representation of the private key (including the public key) as a JSON string ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Generate%20key)). The returned string is a malloc’ed C string in UTF-8. On success, it might look like a JSON with `"kty":"OKP","crv":"Ed25519","x":<pubkey>,"d":<privkey>` etc. **Memory:** Caller must free the returned string with `didkit_free_string`. **Errors:** On failure (which is rare for key generation, barring entropy issues), returns NULL and you can call `didkit_error_message()` to get the error description ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20)).
  - *Note:* DIDKit currently supports Ed25519 key generation via this function. If you need other key types (secp256k1, P-256, etc.), DIDKit does not have dedicated exports for those in the WASM interface (there is no `didkit_vc_generate_secp256k1_key` in the current API). You would generate those keys externally and then use DIDKit’s other functions (like `didkit_key_to_did`) to work with them.
- **`didkit_key_to_did(method: *const c_char, key_jwk: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Derives a DID from a given key. You supply a DID method name (e.g. `"key"`, `"tz"`, `"ethr"`, etc.) and a JWK (private or public) as input. It returns a DID string associated with that key. For example, if `method = "key"` and the JWK is an Ed25519 key, this returns a DID of the form `did:key:z6Mk...` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Adid%20%3D%20didkit_key_to_did%28,key)). For `method = "key"`, it uses the W3C did:key spec (multicodec encoding of the public key). If you provided `"tz"` (Tezos) or `"ethr"`, it would produce a did:tz or did:ethr (assuming the JWK has the required info like an Ethereum address). **Memory:** Returned DID string is allocated and must be freed with `didkit_free_string` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Adid%20%3D%20didkit_key_to_did%28,key)). **Errors:** Returns NULL on failure (e.g. if the method is unsupported or key format is invalid); use `didkit_error_message()` to get the error text.
- **`didkit_key_to_verification_method(method: *const c_char, key_jwk: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Similar to above, but returns the DID URL for the key’s verification method. In other words, it gives the full DID URL that identifies the public key in the DID Document. For `method = "key"`, this typically appends a fragment to the DID (e.g. `did:key:z6Mk...#z6Mk...`) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Averification_method%20%3D%20didkit_key_to_verification_method%28,key)). For other methods, it might construct whatever DID URL format is appropriate (for did:web, a URI to the key in the document; for did:ethr, likely the DID itself with a fragment or path). **Memory:** Must free the returned string with `didkit_free_string`. **Errors:** NULL and use `didkit_error_message` on error.

*(In summary, `didkit_vc_generate_ed25519_key` gives you a new key; `didkit_key_to_did` and `didkit_key_to_verification_method` let you derive identifiers from any given key. Typically, you generate a key, then get its DID and verificationMethod to use in credentials and proofs. In the test example, they generate a key, then compute `did = didkit_key_to_did("key", key)`, and `verificationMethod = didkit_key_to_verification_method("key", key)` to use in the credential ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Adid%20%3D%20didkit_key_to_did%28,key)).)*

### Credential and Presentation Issuance Functions
- **`didkit_vc_issue_credential(credential_json: *const c_char, proof_options_json: *const c_char, key_jwk: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Issues (signs) a Verifiable Credential. You pass in the unsigned credential (as a JSON string), a proof options JSON, and the signing key (as JWK JSON). It returns a string of the Verifiable Credential with an added proof. The proof could be a Linked Data Proof or a JWT, depending on the options. **Parameters:** 
  - `credential_json`: The credential data to sign. This should include `@context`, `type`, `credentialSubject`, etc., but **omit** the `proof` if using Linked Data Proofs (DIDKit will add it) or obviously no signature if JWT. 
  - `proof_options_json`: A JSON string controlling the proof. Options include:
    - `"proofPurpose"`: (required) Purpose of the proof, e.g. `"assertionMethod"` for credentials ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vc_options%2C%20sizeof%20vc_options%2C%20)).
    - `"verificationMethod"`: (optional but recommended) DID URL of the key to use. If not provided, DIDKit might pick one (e.g. the first key) but it’s best to specify it. In practice, you supply the value from `didkit_key_to_verification_method`.
    - `"proofFormat"`: `"ldp"` (default) for a JSON-LD proof or `"jwt"` for a JWT credential ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vc_options%2C%20sizeof%20vc_options%2C%20)).
    - `"created"`, `"expiration"`, `"challenge"`, `"domain"`, etc.: You can include these if needed (if not, DIDKit will set defaults like current timestamp for created).
  - `key_jwk`: The private key to sign with, in JWK JSON format. For Linked Data proofs, DIDKit needs the private key to produce a signature (Ed25519, Ecdsa, etc. as per the DID method). For JWT, DIDKit will use this key to produce a JWS.
  - **Return:** On success, returns a C string containing the full credential JSON, including the `proof` field (for LDP) or the compact JWT string (if `proofFormat: "jwt"` was specified). For example, if you passed `proofFormat: "jwt"`, the return will be a JWT string (which internally is the signed credential).
  - **Memory:** The result is newly allocated; free it with `didkit_free_string` when done ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20,vc_options%2C%20key)).
  - **Errors:** Returns `NULL` on failure; call `didkit_error_message()` to get the error. Common errors could be malformed JSON inputs, unsupported key or proof format, etc. In the DIDKit docs, it notes: *“On failure, NULL is returned, and the error message can be retrieved using didkit_error_message.”* ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=Issue%20a%20Verifiable%20Presentation,be%20retrieved%20using%20%2047)).
- **`didkit_vc_issue_presentation(presentation_json: *const c_char, proof_options_json: *const c_char, key_jwk: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Issues (signs) a Verifiable Presentation. This is analogous to credential issuance but for a Presentation. You provide an unsigned presentation (which typically contains the fields `@context`, `type`:["VerifiablePresentation"], `holder`, and the `verifiableCredential` array of VCs), plus proof options and a key. It returns the presentation with a proof (or as a JWT). The parameters and usage are similar to `vc_issue_credential`, except `proofPurpose` will usually be `"authentication"` or another appropriate purpose for the presentation’s proof ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)). **Example:** you might call this to create a signed presentation for a DID-Auth challenge or to present certain credentials. **Memory and errors:** Same pattern: returns allocated string (to free) or NULL on error with error message ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=Issue%20a%20Verifiable%20Presentation,be%20retrieved%20using%20%2047)). (The DIDKit documentation explicitly notes the need to free the returned string with `didkit_free_string` ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=Issue%20a%20Verifiable%20Presentation,be%20retrieved%20using%20%2047)).)
- **`didkit_did_auth(did: *const c_char, proof_options_json: *const c_char, key_jwk: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Generates a **DID Authentication Verifiable Presentation**. This is a convenience function to produce a presentation that proves control of a DID (often used for challenge-response authentication between agents). Under the hood, it likely creates a minimal Verifiable Presentation with `holder` set to the DID and no credential inside, then signs it. You supply the DID (of the holder), proof options (which should include `"proofPurpose": "authentication"` and typically a `"challenge"` and perhaps `"domain"`), and the private key JWK. It returns a Verifiable Presentation (JWT or LDP depending on `proofFormat`) that the DID holder has signed. In the test code, they use `didkit_did_auth` to produce an authentication VP in both LDP form and JWT form by toggling the `proofFormat` option ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20,vp_options%2C%20key)). **Memory/Errors:** Same deal – free the result string, check `didkit_error_message` on NULL. Essentially, `didkit_did_auth` is a shortcut for a common pattern and spares you from manually constructing the VP JSON.

### Verification Functions
- **`didkit_vc_verify_credential(vc_json_or_jwt: *const c_char, verify_options_json: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Verifies a Verifiable Credential (either a JSON-LD credential with proof, or a JWT credential). You pass the credential data (as a string) and a JSON string of verification options. It returns a JSON string describing the verification result. **Inputs:**
  - `vc_json_or_jwt`: If verifying a Linked Data Proof credential, this should be the full credential JSON including the `proof`. If verifying a JWT, this should be the compact JWS string (the function will detect JWT vs JSON by attempting to parse, especially if you provide the proofFormat option).
  - `verify_options_json`: Options that guide verification. You’ll commonly include:
    - `"proofPurpose"`: e.g. `"assertionMethod"` for VCs ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vc_options%2C%20sizeof%20vc_options%2C%20)), to ensure the proof’s purpose matches and the key is authorized as such. (If not provided, DIDKit might use the proof’s own purpose field by default; but providing it is a good practice).
    - `"proofFormat"`: `"jwt"` if the input is a JWT VC ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Verify%20Credential%20)). Omit or use `"ldp"` for JSON-LD with embedded proof.
    - (There are other possible options like `"challenge"` or `"domain"` if you expect them in the proof, but those are typically for presentations.)
  - **Return:** On success or failure, this function does **not** simply return true/false — instead it returns a JSON report. The report contains fields like `{"errors": [...], "warnings": [...], ...}`. If verification passes with no issues, `"errors"` will be an empty array in the JSON ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Avc_verify_options%20%3D%20,assertionMethod)). If something fails (signature, expiration, etc.), it will list one or more error messages. The DIDKit test uses this by checking if the returned JSON contains `"errors":[]` as an indication of success ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Avc_verify_options%20%3D%20,assertionMethod)). If the verification process itself encounters a runtime error (e.g. bad input), the function can return NULL, and `didkit_error_message` would have details.
  - **Memory:** The result JSON string is allocated in WASM memory; free it with `didkit_free_string` when done ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=didkit_free_string)).
  - **Errors:** If it returns NULL (which means it couldn’t even produce a result JSON), use `didkit_error_message()` to get the error. But normally, even if verification fails, DIDKit still returns a JSON with the errors listed rather than NULL.
- **`didkit_vc_verify_presentation(vp_json_or_jwt: *const c_char, verify_options_json: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Verifies a Verifiable Presentation (either a JSON-LD presentation with proof, or a JWT). Similar to the above, pass the presentation (with proof or the JWT) and options. **Options of note:**
  - `"proofPurpose"`: e.g. `"authentication"` if it’s a DIDAuth or an auth presentation ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20%2Avp_verify_options%20%3D%20,authentication)), or `"assertionMethod"` if you expect the VP’s proof to be for assertions (less common; usually VPs are for auth or something like `delegation` depending on context).
  - `"proofFormat"`: `"jwt"` if the presentation is a JWP/JWT form ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)).
  - `"challenge"` and `"domain"`: if the presentation’s proof contains a challenge (as is typical for DIDAuth), supply the expected challenge string (and domain if applicable) in the verify options ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=char%20didauth_vp_verify_options)) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=snprintf%28vp_options%2C%20sizeof%20vp_options%2C%20)). DIDKit will then ensure the proof’s `challenge` and `domain` match what you provided – this is crucial for security in authentication protocols.
  - **Return:** A JSON string similar to credential verification result, with an `"errors"` array, etc. You must free this string with `didkit_free_string` when done ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=if%20%28strstr%28res%2C%20,s%22%2C%20res)) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=if%20%28strstr%28res%2C%20,s%22%2C%20res)).
  - **Errors:** NULL on low-level failure (then use `didkit_error_message`). Otherwise check the content of the returned JSON for any errors or warnings.

*(Both verify functions do the heavy lifting we described in section 1: resolving DIDs, checking keys and proof purposes, etc. The JSON result makes it easy to see what went wrong if something doesn’t verify.)*

### DID Resolution & Utility Functions
- **`didkit_did_resolve(did: *const c_char, input_metadata_json: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Resolves a DID to a DID Document (plus metadata), following the DID Core resolution algorithm. The first argument is the DID string (e.g. `"did:key:..."` or `"did:web:example.com:..."`). The second is an optional JSON string for resolution options (you can pass `NULL` or `"{}"` for defaults). It returns a JSON string containing the **DID Resolution Result** object as per the DID spec. This JSON typically has shape: `{"didDocument": {...}, "didDocumentMetadata": {...}, "didResolutionMetadata": {...}}`. In the test, for example, calling `didkit_did_resolve` on a did:key returned JSON where they could find `"didDocument": { ... }` inside ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Resolve%20DID)). **Memory:** The result is allocated (often a pretty large JSON string); free it with `didkit_free_string` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=%2F%2F%20Resolve%20DID)). **Errors:** If resolution fails (e.g. unsupported DID method, network error for did:web, etc.), returns NULL and you can get the error message via `didkit_error_message`. (Note: In a WASM context without WASI, methods that require network like did:web or did:ion might not work unless the WASM was compiled with networking or provided resolver hooks. did:key and others that are purely algorithmic will work offline. Ensure any needed DID methods are supported by DIDKit’s compiled-in methods list ([didkit - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit#:~:text=%2A%20%20did,webkey%20%5E0.2%20normal)).)
- **`didkit_did_url_dereference(did_url: *const c_char, input_metadata_json: *const c_char)` → `*const c_char`** – Dereferences a DID URL to a resource. This is essentially the DID URL dereference algorithm from the DID Core spec, implemented by DIDKit. You pass a DID URL (which could be a DID with fragment to a key, or a service endpoint DID URL, etc.) and optional options. It returns a JSON string that typically contains the resource or the result of dereferencing. For example, if you pass a DID URL that points to a verification method (key) in the DID Document, this might return the public key material. In the test code, `didkit_did_url_dereference(verification_method, NULL)` returns a JSON array (perhaps the representation(s) of the key) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20,NULL)). **Memory:** Free the returned string with `didkit_free_string` ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=const%20char%20,NULL)). **Errors:** Returns NULL on error (e.g. if the DID URL is invalid or cannot be resolved) – check `didkit_error_message` for info.
- **`didkit_error_message()` → `*const c_char`** – Retrieves the last error message produced by a DIDKit operation. After any DIDKit function returns NULL to signal an error, you call this to get a human-readable error string. For example, if `didkit_vc_issue_credential` fails, calling `didkit_error_message()` might return something like `"Unsupported key type"` or `"Invalid JSON"` depending on what went wrong ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=if%20,s%22%2C%20didkit_error_message)). **Important:** The string returned by `didkit_error_message` is managed by DIDKit internally. In the docs, they don’t explicitly mention freeing it, and in practice the test code does *not* free the result of `didkit_error_message()` (they just print it) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=vp%20%3D%20didkit_vc_issue_presentation)). This implies the error message is likely stored in a static buffer or otherwise does not require manual free (or the program exits on error so it didn’t matter). To be safe, you could call `didkit_free_string` on it if you plan to call many times, but it’s probably not necessary – consider it read-only and short-lived. Always call it *immediately after* a failure; if another DIDKit function is invoked, the error state may be overwritten.
- **`didkit_free_string(str_ptr: *const c_char)` → `void`** – Frees an allocated string that was returned by one of the DIDKit functions. Every function that returns a `*const c_char` which is a result or JSON data expects you to free it when done. The test code frees every result string, credential, presentation, DID, etc., using this function ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=didkit_free_string)) ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=match%20at%20L847%20didkit_free_string)). You should **not** free strings that you did not receive from DIDKit (for example, the input strings you pass in – those are your responsibility in host code, not DIDKit’s). Also, do not use `didkit_free_string` on the same pointer twice (after freeing, the memory is gone). Essentially it’s analogous to `free()` for the WASM module’s heap. It does not return anything.

**String encoding and pointers:** All string parameters and return values are UTF-8 encoded and null-terminated. When calling these functions via Wasmtime, you must ensure the input C strings are allocated in the module’s memory and terminated with a 0 byte. For outputs, DIDKit returns a pointer (an integer offset in WASM linear memory) where the string is stored, or 0 (NULL) on error ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=Issue%20a%20Verifiable%20Presentation,be%20retrieved%20using%20%2047)). The Python code needs to read from the module’s memory at that pointer to retrieve the actual string bytes.

**Example of calling from Python (Wasmtime):** Suppose you want to call `didkit_vc_issue_credential`. You would do something like:
1. Allocate memory in the WASM for the inputs. The DIDKit module exports a linear memory (accessible via `instance.exports["memory"]`). You can get a Python view of this memory buffer. For example, Wasmtime’s Python API allows obtaining a pointer or a writable buffer for the memory data. You would copy your JSON strings (credential JSON, options JSON, key JSON) into WASM memory and note their offsets. (Ensure each string is null-terminated in memory.)
2. Invoke the function export with those offsets. For instance: `result_ptr = instance.exports(store)["didkit_vc_issue_credential"](cred_ptr, options_ptr, key_ptr)`. The function will return an integer pointer (e.g. an offset like 1024) where the signed credential string resides in memory.
3. Check the return. If `result_ptr == 0`, an error occurred. You can then call `err_ptr = instance.exports(store)["didkit_error_message"]()` to get the error string pointer, and read that from memory similarly to get the message.
4. If `result_ptr` is nonzero, read the C-string from memory. You can read byte-by-byte until you hit `0x00` (the terminator) to reconstruct the UTF-8 string. Wasmtime’s memory API can help – for example, in Rust you can do `memory.data_ptr(&caller).offset(result_ptr)` to get the address ([webassembly - Pass a pointer string as an argument in host import function in Rust WebAassembly (wasmtime) - Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/67434474/pass-a-pointer-string-as-an-argument-in-host-import-function-in-rust-webaassembl#:~:text=let%20memory%20%3D%20caller.get_export%28,)). In Python, you might use `memory.buffer` or a memory view slice to read bytes starting at `result_ptr`.
5. Don’t forget to free the returned string by calling the `didkit_free_string` export with `result_ptr` as argument ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=didkit_free_string)). This frees WASM heap memory. (The memory for your inputs can be reused or left – they were provided by you, so manage them as needed; often you can allocate them in a scratch area and reuse that area for subsequent calls.)

For convenience, you could write helper functions in Python to wrap this pointer juggling – e.g. an `invoke_didkit(func_name, *args)` that handles encoding strings to UTF-8, allocating them in memory, calling the function, and decoding/freeing results. This would hide the manual steps. If this sounds complex, note that the official `didkit-python` bindings (if used natively via cffi) handle this for you; but since you’re doing pure WASM with Wasmtime, you have to manage memory yourself.

To summarize, the WASM interface is low-level but straightforward:
- All inputs/outputs are C strings (UTF-8 + null terminator) except the free function.
- Allocate inputs in WASM memory, call function, then retrieve output from WASM memory.
- Use `didkit_free_string` for every output string when done.
- Use `didkit_error_message` for diagnosing errors (after a function returns NULL).
Each function’s exact signature in C terms can be found in DIDKit’s C header (or docs), and they match the pattern described above ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=,%2Aconst%20c_char)) ([didkit_vc_issue_presentation in didkit::c - Rust](https://docs.rs/didkit/latest/didkit/c/fn.didkit_vc_issue_presentation.html#:~:text=Issue%20a%20Verifiable%20Presentation,be%20retrieved%20using%20%2047)).

## 3. VC Structure Optimization for Machine Identity

The current minimal credential format you provided is a bare-bones Verifiable Credential. It’s functional, but we can improve it for clarity, security, and interoperability, especially for an agent-to-agent authentication scenario in the Vela Network.

Your example credential (in JSON) is:

```json
{
  "@context": ["https://www.w3.org/2018/credentials/v1"],
  "type": ["VerifiableCredential"],
  "issuanceDate": "2023-01-01T00:00:00Z",
  "credentialSubject": {
    "message": "..."
  }
}
```

Here are recommendations to enhance this for machine identity use:

- **Include an `issuer` field:** In the W3C Verifiable Credentials Data Model, the `issuer` property is usually required (it indicates who issued the credential). You should add `"issuer": "<DID of the issuer>"` to the top-level. If the agent is using a self-issued credential (it signs its own credential to present to others), then the `issuer` would be the agent’s own DID. If a central authority issues credentials to each agent, then `issuer` would be that authority’s DID. Including this field makes the credential more explicit and standard-compliant ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=)). It also allows verifiers to quickly see who issued the credential without digging into the proof. (In JWT credentials, the `issuer` field corresponds to the JWT’s `iss` claim, which DIDKit will set accordingly if present ([Verifiable Credential - EBSI hub](https://hub.ebsi.eu/tools/libraries/verifiable-credential#:~:text=Verifiable%20Credential%20,The%20jti%20property%20must)).)
- **Include `credentialSubject.id`:** Right now, the credentialSubject has only a `message`. To bind the credential to the identity of an agent, you should include an identifier for the subject. For example: 
  ```json
  "credentialSubject": {
      "id": "<DID of the subject>",
      "message": "..."
  }
  ``` 
  If the credential is self-issued, the `credentialSubject.id` can be the same as the issuer DID (meaning “I, DID X, assert something about DID X”). In other cases, it could be different (issuer issues a credential to subject DID Y). Including the subject’s DID makes it clear which agent this credential refers to ([didkit/lib/c/test.c at main · spruceid/didkit · GitHub](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit/blob/main/lib/c/test.c#:~:text=)). In machine authentication, this is likely the DID of the agent presenting the credential. This also aligns with JWT usage, where the subject would map to the `sub` claim in a JWT VC (which should match credentialSubject.id) ([Verifiable Credential - EBSI hub](https://hub.ebsi.eu/tools/libraries/verifiable-credential#:~:text=Verifiable%20Credential%20,The%20jti%20property%20must)).
- **Credential `type`:** Using `"VerifiableCredential"` as a type is correct. You can extend the `type` array with a more specific type to indicate the credential’s purpose or schema. For example, you might add `"AgentCredential"` or `"AuthenticationCredential"` (ensure you have a context for any new type if it implies new fields). For instance: `"type": ["VerifiableCredential", "AgentCredential"]`. This doesn’t directly affect verification, but it can communicate the intent of the credential to others and allow future extension. It’s not strictly necessary, but if you have a profile for your machine credentials, a custom type helps interoperability (others will know what kind of credential it is).
- **Add an `id` for the credential (optional):** It can be good to include an `"id"` property at the top level of the credential (a URI or DID URL identifying this credential instance uniquely). This is recommended in the VC spec for traceability. For example, `"id": "urn:uuid:...some unique id..."` or a DID URL. If your use case doesn’t need to reference the credential later, this can be skipped, but it’s a harmless addition that improves standards compliance.
- **Use `issuer` and `subject` to bind identity:** By having both issuer and credentialSubject.id, you clearly delineate the parties. In a self-issued scenario, you end up with issuer == subject DID, which is effectively a statement “I assert my own identity” – somewhat redundant but it’s the standard way (it’s like a self-signed certificate). The real proof of control comes from the signature (the proof) anyway, but including these fields makes the credential a complete, stand-alone object that is easier for any verifier (or any VC tool) to understand and use.
- **Consider an expiration or rotation mechanism:** For authentication credentials used in a network, you might not want credentials to last forever (in case an agent is compromised or leaves the network). Consider adding `"expirationDate": "<timestamp>"` in the VC. This way, verifiers will reject credentials after a certain date, and agents will periodically refresh or get new credentials. DIDKit will automatically check `expirationDate` during verification and list an error if the credential is expired (in the `VerificationResult` it returns).
- **Minimize the `credentialSubject` data or standardize it:** If the VC is purely for authentication, you might not need a `message` field at all – unless you are trying to convey some ephemeral message or challenge. Often, authentication is done by presenting a VC that just says “I am X” and was issued by either X itself or some authority. If you want to include a random challenge or one-time message, that’s typically done via the proof (e.g. the challenge in a VP’s proof as we see with DIDAuth) rather than as a field in the VC. If `"message"` is just a static statement, consider whether it’s needed. If it’s dynamic (like a challenge), then the VC itself would be changing each time which is unusual – typically one would not issue a brand new credential for each auth, but rather use a presentation with a challenge. For agent-to-agent, a simpler approach could be each agent has a long-lived VC for its identity (with issuer and subject as itself, possibly with an expiry), and when authenticating, it wraps that VC in a presentation with a challenge. This way the VC is like an identity certificate, and the presentation proves freshness.
- **Ensure the context is sufficient:** You already include the base VC context. If you add fields like `expirationDate` or a custom type or use a specific proof type, make sure the contexts cover those. For example, the base context covers `VerifiableCredential`, `issuer`, `credentialSubject`, and basic fields. If you use `expirationDate`, it’s defined in the base context as well (so you’re fine). If you introduce a custom field or type, you might need a custom context. For instance, if you decided to add a field `"role": "sensor"` in credentialSubject to indicate the type of agent, you’d want a context defining `"role"`. Interoperability improves when you stick to standard fields or properly define new ones.
- **Use standard proof types:** Since you’re using DIDKit, by default if you issue an LDP it will likely use Ed25519Signature2018 or 2020 with a corresponding security context. The output credential from DIDKit (if LDP) should include a `proof` with a `type` and `verificationMethod`. Ensure that any required context (e.g. `https://w3id.org/security/v2`) is present. DIDKit usually handles adding the context for you if needed when it adds the proof, but double-check. For JWT, the proof isn’t a JSON-LD object but the JWT itself carries the claims. DIDKit maps fields like issuer/subject as noted. Using these standard proof formats ensures other parties can verify the credential in a standard way.

**Issuer field and trust model:** If every agent is just using self-issued credentials, the system is effectively using DIDs themselves as identities (the VC just wraps it). That is okay for establishing mutual TLS-like identity (you prove control of your DID by signing something). However, think about whether you want an authority or registry to vouch for DIDs. In Phase 1, perhaps not – maybe any DID is accepted. In that case, a self-signed VC is equivalent to just presenting a DID. But one benefit of a VC is you could easily integrate a trust authority later: e.g., in Phase 2, you might introduce an issuer that signs all agent credentials (making it more like a PKI where the issuer is a root of trust). Your VC format should be compatible with that future change. By including the `issuer` field now (even if it’s self), you won’t have to redesign the VC format later.

To maximize **interoperability**, aligning with the W3C spec is key: use the standard fields (`issuer`, `credentialSubject.id`, `issuanceDate`, `expirationDate`, etc.) and standard proof methods. This way, any W3C-conformant verifier (not just DIDKit) could interpret the credentials. Also, if you plan to use OpenID for VC presentations or other protocols, having issuer and subject IDs that map cleanly to `iss` and `sub` is important (as noted, `iss` should equal VC issuer, `sub` equals credentialSubject.id in JWT VC) ([Verifiable Credential - EBSI hub](https://hub.ebsi.eu/tools/libraries/verifiable-credential#:~:text=Verifiable%20Credential%20,The%20jti%20property%20must)). DIDKit already adheres to those mappings.

**Summary of recommendations for the VC format:**
- Add `"issuer": "<agentDID>"` (yes, always include it).
- Add `"credentialSubject": { "id": "<agentDID>", ... }` to bind the identity (use the agent’s DID here).
- Consider a custom `"type"` to identify the VC’s purpose (optional).
- Consider `"expirationDate": "...some future date..."` to enforce credential renewal.
- Keep using the base context, and add contexts only if you introduce non-standard fields.
- Ensure that when you issue the VC with DIDKit, you pass appropriate proof purpose (`assertionMethod`) so that the proof is tied to the issuer’s DID (DIDKit will automatically include `issuer` in the JWT claims or you include it in the JSON, and will include `credentialSubject.id` in JWT as `sub` if present).
- Use a Verifiable Presentation for the actual authentication handshake: The holder (agent) can present this VC (perhaps along with others) in a VP, proving control via a fresh signature (with a challenge from the verifier). DIDKit’s `didkit_did_auth` is a neat shortcut for that, as it essentially does exactly this – creates a VP with `holder` DID and signs it. However, `didkit_did_auth` by itself doesn’t include your credential – it’s just a proof of DID control. You might want the agent to send *both* a proof of DID control *and* its credential. This can be done by creating a VP that includes the VC as `verifiableCredential` and is signed by the agent (that covers both identity info and proof of control). You can do that with `didkit_vc_issue_presentation` by including the VC in the presentation JSON.

By following these improvements, your machine identity credentials will be more robust. They will explicitly state who issued them and to whom they belong, aiding verification. They’ll also be forward-compatible with other systems and easier to extend with trust frameworks (like if later you only trust credentials issued by a specific DID, you can check the issuer field).

## 4. Production Hardening and Mock Elimination

In the current setup, there is a mechanism to fall back to a `mock_didkit.py` (with fake signing/verifying) when not in production, controlled by an environment flag `VELA_PRODUCTION_MODE` in `did_utils.py`. While this is useful for testing, it poses **security risks** if not tightly controlled. Here are recommendations to harden the system for production and eliminate insecure fallbacks:

- **Disable and isolate mock functionality in production:** Ensure that when `VELA_PRODUCTION_MODE` is true (or when running in the production environment), none of the mock functions can ever be invoked. The simplest approach is to structure your code such that the mock implementation isn’t even imported or accessible in production. For example, guard the import or usage of `mock_didkit` with a check, and if production mode, perhaps even raise an error if one tries to call a mock. Remove any logic that *silently* switches to the mock on error – in production, an error from DIDKit should be treated as a hard failure, not an excuse to use the insecure stub. This prevents an attacker from manipulating environment or forcing an error to bypass real verification. **In other words, fail closed, not open.**

- **Explicit production gating:** It’s good that you have `VELA_PRODUCTION_MODE`. Make sure this flag is set correctly and cannot be overridden by untrusted input. In production deployment, set it as an environment variable or config and perhaps even bake it into the build (depending on your deployment process). As a fail-safe, you might invert the logic: e.g. require an explicit `DEV_MODE` to enable mocks, otherwise default to secure. That way, if the variable is not set at all, you’re in secure mode. Also, consider logging the mode on startup so it’s clear which path the code is using.

- **WASM module integrity check:** The `didkit.wasm` binary itself becomes a critical piece of your security. Treat it like you would any cryptographic library binary. In production, you should verify that you’re loading a genuine DIDKit WASM and that it hasn’t been tampered with. One approach is to maintain a known good hash (SHA-256, for example) of the WASM file and, at application startup, compute the hash of the deployed `didkit.wasm` and compare it. If it doesn’t match, refuse to run or log a critical error. This ensures an attacker hasn’t swapped out the WASM with a malicious one. Additionally, ensure the WASM file is read from a secure location (not an arbitrary path where it could be replaced by less privileged processes). If possible, bundle it with your application in a way that it’s not easy to override without deploying new code.

- **Validate cryptographic operations at startup (self-test):** In production, perform a quick self-test of DIDKit’s functionality on startup. For example, generate a test key, issue a credential, and verify it, or use a known test vector. This serves two purposes: (1) It ensures that the WASM is functioning and the host integration (memory, calls) is correct. (2) It ensures that the cryptographic path isn’t silently failing and falling back to mock. If the self-test fails and you detect that somehow a mock was used or the results are incorrect, you can stop the service initialization. This is similar to how some cryptographic modules perform power-on self-tests to ensure they are not corrupted. Keep the test simple and quick (it can be as basic as signing a hello world credential and verifying it). If using a fixed test vector, ensure it wouldn’t be mistaken for real data (only in memory). This also catches any misconfiguration early.

- **No silent fallback – loud failure instead:** Remove any code that automatically swaps in the fake implementation when something goes wrong without alerting. Instead, if an attempt to use DIDKit fails in production (e.g. the WASM cannot be loaded, or a signing operation throws an exception), log an error to your monitoring system and refuse the operation. You might even want to terminate the service startup if the core crypto module isn’t working, rather than running in a degraded (and insecure) mode. The rationale is that it’s better to fail to issue/verify credentials (and thus not authenticate) than to unknowingly accept credentials without real verification. For example, if `didkit.wasm` failed to load and your code then used `mock_didkit.verify_credential` which just returns True for any signature, that would be a catastrophic silent failure. So ensure there's no path that does that without very noisy logging and explicit operator intervention.

- **Logging and monitoring:** In production, log the version or hash of DIDKit WASM you loaded (so you know which build is running). Also log any errors from DIDKit (via `didkit_error_message`) at a high severity. If for some reason you ever do allow a fallback (not recommended), it should log an alert like “CRYPTO FALLBACK ACTIVATED – USING INSECURE MOCK” so that it’s impossible to miss in logs. Ideally, integrate with monitoring/alerting to page someone if that ever happens in production.

- **Eliminate the mock code when building for production:** If your deployment process can differentiate environments, you could literally omit the `mock_didkit.py` from the production build or package. That way, even if someone tried to import it, it fails. Another approach is to require a specific flag to enable the mock (like a `--allow-insecure` flag only used in tests). The goal is to make it *hard* to run insecurely by accident.

- **Secure deployment of the WASM binary:** Besides checking integrity, ensure the WASM is the correct version that you intend to use (for example, always use the latest audited version of DIDKit). Spruce (the maintainers of DIDKit) have had security audits ([GitHub - spruceid/didkit: A cross-platform toolkit for decentralized identity.](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit#:~:text=Security%20Audits)) on the library, which is good – leverage that by using official builds. Don’t modify the WASM in ways that aren’t needed. If you build it from source, do so in a controlled environment. In production, store the WASM file in a read-only directory or package it into your application resources. If possible, restrict filesystem or network access for the WASM (Wasmtime can be configured to not allow WASI FS or net unless explicitly needed – if your use-case doesn’t need DID methods that hit the network, you could run the module in a sandbox with no WASI imports, making it harder for a tampered WASM to exfiltrate anything).

- **Error handling improvements:** Wrap calls to DIDKit in try/except (or equivalent) so that any unexpected exception is caught and handled. For instance, if `instance.exports["didkit_vc_issue_credential"]` throws an error in Python (maybe memory issue or so), catch it and treat it as a critical failure. Also ensure to free strings in a `finally` block to avoid memory leaks on exceptions. On verification, if `didkit_vc_verify_credential` returns a result JSON that contains errors, treat that as a failed verification (do not ignore the errors array). Basically, interpret the output strictly – if any errors are present, authentication should be denied.

- **Test the gating logic:** Before going live, intentionally toggle `VELA_PRODUCTION_MODE` and ensure that in production mode the mocks truly can’t operate. You might write a unit test that monkeypatches the real didkit functions to fail and sees that no credential can be verified rather than the mock taking over. This will confirm that your hardening works.

In summary, the guiding principle is to **trust the real cryptography and distrust the mock**. The mock should be completely out of the picture when real keys and credentials are in use. By verifying the WASM module’s integrity and enforcing its usage, you ensure the system’s cryptographic trust isn’t accidentally or maliciously undermined. Also, leveraging DIDKit’s reliability (which has been audited by security professionals ([GitHub - spruceid/didkit: A cross-platform toolkit for decentralized identity.](https://github.com/spruceid/didkit#:~:text=Security%20Audits))) is far superior to any fake implementation in production. So, all switches should default to “secure or nothing.” With these measures, your autonomous agents will only accept verifiable, genuine credentials, and any failure in the crypto layer will be visible and not silently bypassed. This hardening process reduces the risk of credentials being accepted without proper verification and increases the overall trust in your machine identity system.